ce:section.ce:para:
In this paper it has been shown that “re-thinkingd” sludge management systems require:

                           •

assessing management paths capable of maximizing the recycle/recovery benefits;


                           •

using technically, ecologically and economically feasible methods to reduce sludge quantity at the appropriate level, and not necessarily to the minimum one;


                           •

limiting at the source of harmful substances entering the plant;


                           •

adopting multiple options for sludge destination able to be adapted to local market variabilities;


                           •

developing realistic and enforceable regulation adapted to the local context, including clear rules for penalties and sanctions, supported by standardized characterization procedures and guidelines for good management practices involving citizens and stakeholders in an on-going open dialogue based on mutual trust and respect;


                           •

defining the treatment(s) necessary to optimize the entire system through the development of self-sustaining energy systems, or systems with a low energy environmental impact;


                           •

developing operational systems appropriate to local and site-specific circumstances.
